00:03:36.130 --> 00:03:38.135
All right, so what is an RBMK?

00:03:38.135 --> 00:03:43.210
An RBMK is a light water-cooled,
graphite-moderated,

00:03:43.210 --> 00:03:44.900
channel-type reactor.

00:03:44.900 --> 00:03:47.860
This means that it does not
have a giant pressure vessel

00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:51.430
like you would see in a VVER
or an equivalent American

00:03:51.430 --> 00:03:53.590
light water reactor.

00:03:53.590 --> 00:03:54.860
Why does that mean anything?

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:58.120
Well, building giant pressure
vessels is very difficult.

00:03:58.120 --> 00:04:00.490
If any of you've done
research on manufacturing

00:04:00.490 --> 00:04:02.980
of nuclear reactors,
you'll find out

00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:05.772
that the equipment necessary
to construct a reactor

00:04:05.772 --> 00:04:07.480
pressure vessel is
not actually something

00:04:07.480 --> 00:04:09.850
we even have in the US anymore.

00:04:09.850 --> 00:04:11.820
Is it Korea that
does it for us now?

00:04:11.820 --> 00:04:13.195
MICHAEL SHORT:
Japan Steel Works.

00:04:13.195 --> 00:04:15.550
JAKE HECLA: Japan
that does it now.

00:04:15.550 --> 00:04:18.790
In the Soviet times, it
was very, very difficult

00:04:18.790 --> 00:04:23.860
for the Soviet Union to
produce such pressure vessels

00:04:23.860 --> 00:04:25.480
at any kind of reasonable rate.

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:29.680
So the RBMK got
around this by using

00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:32.500
individual channels that were
their own pressure vessel,

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:33.650
so to speak.

00:04:33.650 --> 00:04:36.700
So the way this works is, let's
just start on the cold side.

00:04:36.700 --> 00:04:40.240
You take in cold water, goes
here through these things.

00:04:40.240 --> 00:04:42.340
These are main
circulating pumps--

00:04:42.340 --> 00:04:43.990
MCPs, as you'll
see them referred

00:04:43.990 --> 00:04:45.760
to later in the presentation--

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:47.930
goes up through the
bottom up the core.

00:04:47.930 --> 00:04:50.440
These are the hot fuel rods.

00:04:50.440 --> 00:04:55.060
The water goes from liquid
to steam phase as it's

00:04:55.060 --> 00:04:59.290
flowing through the
channels, comes out the top,

00:04:59.290 --> 00:05:02.260
goes to the steam
water separators.

00:05:02.260 --> 00:05:04.810
Steam goes to the turbines,
turns the turbines,

00:05:04.810 --> 00:05:06.460
makes electricity.

00:05:06.460 --> 00:05:08.860
The important thing
to remember here

00:05:08.860 --> 00:05:11.950
is that we've got a
giant graphite core.

00:05:11.950 --> 00:05:13.840
The graphite is what
is doing the moderating

00:05:13.840 --> 00:05:15.010
in this circumstance.

00:05:15.010 --> 00:05:18.220
It is not the water.

00:05:18.220 --> 00:05:20.990
This allows you to run
very low-enriched uranium.

00:05:20.990 --> 00:05:24.880
So you could
theoretically run an RBMK

00:05:24.880 --> 00:05:30.340
on I believe it was 1.2 percent
was as low as they could go.

00:05:30.340 --> 00:05:33.150
But regardless, extremely
low-enriched uranium,

00:05:33.150 --> 00:05:35.650
which is convenient if you don't
want to waste a lot of time

00:05:35.650 --> 00:05:36.400
enriching uranium.

00:05:39.910 --> 00:05:44.110
The problem with this is
that you have a giant core.

00:05:44.110 --> 00:05:47.150
If you recall the scattering
cross-section for graphite,

00:05:47.150 --> 00:05:48.880
it's pretty small.

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:51.040
And the amount of energy
lost per collision

00:05:51.040 --> 00:05:53.470
is likewise also fairly small.

00:05:53.470 --> 00:05:58.360
So the core on this thing
is, let's see, 11, yeah,

00:05:58.360 --> 00:06:01.030
11.5 meters across.

00:06:01.030 --> 00:06:04.480
The core for an equivalent
American reactor--

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:07.180
so well, there is no
real equivalent to this--

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:10.720
but for, let's say,
an AP 1000 reactor

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:14.680
of equivalent electrical output,
is about four meters across.

00:06:14.680 --> 00:06:16.705
So the core is huge.

00:06:19.660 --> 00:06:24.520
As I already discussed, this
is what the individual pressure

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:25.540
channels look like.

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:29.020
So cool water comes in the
bottom, goes by the fuel rods,

00:06:29.020 --> 00:06:32.240
pops out the top.

00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:34.720
The RBMK had some
serious design flaws.

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:36.610
So as I said, the core is huge.

00:06:36.610 --> 00:06:38.590
This allows local
power anomalies

00:06:38.590 --> 00:06:41.950
to form really, really easily.

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:43.900
If you look at the
core, one portion

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:46.690
can be kind of neutronically
separated from the others

00:06:46.690 --> 00:06:51.010
because neutrons just don't
make it all that far when

00:06:51.010 --> 00:06:52.150
diffusing across the core.

00:06:52.150 --> 00:06:54.400
So you can have very, very
high power in one corner

00:06:54.400 --> 00:06:58.060
and very low power in the other,
which is not something that

00:06:58.060 --> 00:07:02.170
can develop in a physically
smaller core, which

00:07:02.170 --> 00:07:05.410
has a characteristic
scale equivalent to that

00:07:05.410 --> 00:07:06.790
of the neutron being free path.

00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:13.460
Further, the encore flux
monitoring on the RBMK

00:07:13.460 --> 00:07:15.530
is seriously deficient.

00:07:15.530 --> 00:07:18.260
So there are a variety
of neutron detectors

00:07:18.260 --> 00:07:20.630
that exist around the
periphery of the core.

00:07:20.630 --> 00:07:23.510
But they're wholly insufficient
to catch these local power

00:07:23.510 --> 00:07:24.920
anomalies.

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:27.170
Chernobyl actually found out
the hard way on this one.

00:07:27.170 --> 00:07:32.420
In 1982, unit 1 suffered a
quote "localized core melt,"

00:07:32.420 --> 00:07:36.410
not really something that
can happen in LWR, really

00:07:36.410 --> 00:07:38.000
any other type of reactor.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:39.800
But a couple of
the fuel channels

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:42.320
actually experienced
one of these local power

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:44.060
anomalies and ended up melting.

00:07:44.060 --> 00:07:47.660
So if you go into the
control room of unit 1,

00:07:47.660 --> 00:07:51.760
you can see that on the fuel
channel cartogram on the wall,

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:53.870
there are two of them that
are just Sharpied out.

00:07:53.870 --> 00:07:56.810
And those are the
ones that melted.

00:07:56.810 --> 00:07:59.917
Further, it has a positive
void reactivity coefficient.

00:07:59.917 --> 00:08:00.750
What does that mean?

00:08:00.750 --> 00:08:03.950
Well, when the water
boils in the core,

00:08:03.950 --> 00:08:06.380
the density of the
water there goes down.

00:08:06.380 --> 00:08:08.660
And the power of
the reactor ends up

00:08:08.660 --> 00:08:10.940
going up because the
water is primarily

00:08:10.940 --> 00:08:13.910
acting not as moderator
but as a neutron absorber.

00:08:13.910 --> 00:08:18.230
This is bad for a whole
variety of reasons.

00:08:18.230 --> 00:08:20.570
And they found out
quite catastrophically

00:08:20.570 --> 00:08:22.400
in 1986 exactly why.

00:08:22.400 --> 00:08:26.390
Further, the system is
extremely unstable at low power.

00:08:30.470 --> 00:08:34.580
So how did the 1986
accident happen?

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:39.700
It was part of this thing called
a turbo generator rundown test.

00:08:39.700 --> 00:08:44.200
The general idea is that if you
have an off-site power failure,

00:08:44.200 --> 00:08:47.650
and your main circulating
pumps are no longer

00:08:47.650 --> 00:08:49.447
have off-site power,
you somehow need

00:08:49.447 --> 00:08:51.280
to keep water flowing
through the core, such

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:53.950
that the fuel does not melt.

00:08:53.950 --> 00:08:57.580
The problem is that the backup,
large diesel generators,

00:08:57.580 --> 00:08:58.180
are just that.

00:08:58.180 --> 00:08:59.030
They're large.

00:08:59.030 --> 00:09:00.040
They're diesel.

00:09:00.040 --> 00:09:01.600
And therefore they're
very, very slow

00:09:01.600 --> 00:09:04.720
to come online and
come up to full power.

00:09:04.720 --> 00:09:06.790
The way that you
can bridge this gap

00:09:06.790 --> 00:09:10.360
is by using the energy that
you've stored in the turbines

00:09:10.360 --> 00:09:12.760
to effectively power the
main circulating pumps

00:09:12.760 --> 00:09:15.940
until the diesel generators
can come up online.

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:19.840
When unit 4 was fully
constructed in 1983

00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:21.410
and turned on for
the first time,

00:09:21.410 --> 00:09:23.250
they had never
actually done this test

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:25.210
where they did a turbo
generator rundown,

00:09:25.210 --> 00:09:27.970
despite the fact that it was
required by law in the Soviet

00:09:27.970 --> 00:09:30.670
Union that all new
power stations should

00:09:30.670 --> 00:09:32.370
have this test performed.

00:09:32.370 --> 00:09:35.890
It was delayed until 1986.

00:09:35.890 --> 00:09:43.940
And yeah, it was delayed until
1986 is the long story short.

00:09:43.940 --> 00:09:46.720
The test procedure-- sorry for
all the text on this slide--

00:09:46.720 --> 00:09:48.440
is basically as follows.

00:09:48.440 --> 00:09:50.320
So you would ramp
the reactor down.

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:52.810
So you would bring it from
a normal thermal output

00:09:52.810 --> 00:09:56.230
of up to 2,400
megawatts thermal,

00:09:56.230 --> 00:09:59.240
down to 600 or 700 megawatts.

00:09:59.240 --> 00:10:01.378
You'd bring the turbo
generators up to full speed.

00:10:01.378 --> 00:10:02.920
So you'd store as
much energy in them

00:10:02.920 --> 00:10:06.910
as you possibly could, then
cut off the steam supply such

00:10:06.910 --> 00:10:09.760
that now you are just extracting
energy from the spinning turbo

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:11.242
generator.

00:10:11.242 --> 00:10:13.450
This would then be used to
power the main circulating

00:10:13.450 --> 00:10:16.930
pumps, each of which
took about 40 megawatts.

00:10:16.930 --> 00:10:19.180
There are eight of them total.

00:10:19.180 --> 00:10:23.950
I believe six could be
used for normal operation.

00:10:23.950 --> 00:10:26.080
The rundown would take
somewhere in the range

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:27.940
of 60 to 70 seconds.

00:10:27.940 --> 00:10:30.010
And hopefully by this time
your diesel generators

00:10:30.010 --> 00:10:31.690
would be turned
on, pumping water,

00:10:31.690 --> 00:10:33.740
and everything would be fine.

00:10:33.740 --> 00:10:36.940
What happened in the test
was decidedly quite different

00:10:36.940 --> 00:10:37.840
from that.

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:43.420
So on April 26,
1986, they attempted

00:10:43.420 --> 00:10:46.390
to begin this test about
six hours behind schedule

00:10:46.390 --> 00:10:49.360
because there was an incident
in another part of Ukraine,

00:10:49.360 --> 00:10:51.550
in which a coal power
plant went offline.

00:10:51.550 --> 00:10:55.450
So what happened
was the authority

00:10:55.450 --> 00:10:58.450
for the grid in the area
ordered that Chernobyl

00:10:58.450 --> 00:11:03.970
should stay online at full power
for an additional six hours.

00:11:03.970 --> 00:11:06.730
They began the test by
bringing power down.

00:11:06.730 --> 00:11:11.470
But as a result of running
for an extra six hours,

00:11:11.470 --> 00:11:14.260
they'd built up a significant
amount of xenon precursors

00:11:14.260 --> 00:11:15.290
in the core.

00:11:15.290 --> 00:11:17.890
So when they started
turning the power down,

00:11:17.890 --> 00:11:21.160
the power started going
down, and down, and down.

00:11:21.160 --> 00:11:26.050
And they were unable
to arrest its drop.

00:11:26.050 --> 00:11:29.680
What ended up happening was that
the power dropped all the way

00:11:29.680 --> 00:11:31.870
down to 30 megawatts thermal.

00:11:31.870 --> 00:11:35.330
And the reactor operators
kind of panicked.

00:11:35.330 --> 00:11:38.350
Their response to this,
instead of canceling the test,

00:11:38.350 --> 00:11:40.570
was to pull out as
many control rods

00:11:40.570 --> 00:11:42.220
as they could get
their hands on.

00:11:42.220 --> 00:11:42.940
They did so.

00:11:42.940 --> 00:11:46.840
And this managed to rescue the
thermal output of the reactor.

00:11:46.840 --> 00:11:50.170
And it bumped up to around
200 megawatts thermal.

00:11:50.170 --> 00:11:53.440
At this point, the reactor was
in an extremely unstable state.

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:56.170
Mind you, almost all of the rods
that they could get their hands

00:11:56.170 --> 00:11:58.150
on were out of the reactor.

00:11:58.150 --> 00:11:59.950
The only thing
keeping reactivity

00:11:59.950 --> 00:12:01.600
at a reasonable level
was all the xenon

00:12:01.600 --> 00:12:04.660
that was built up in the core.

00:12:04.660 --> 00:12:08.410
At this point, they began the
turbo generator run down test.

00:12:08.410 --> 00:12:14.110
They shut off steam to the main
turbine, or one of the turbines

00:12:14.110 --> 00:12:17.560
after it was run
up to full power,

00:12:17.560 --> 00:12:20.350
and then attempted to run
the main circulating pump.

00:12:20.350 --> 00:12:23.500
The main circulating pump
started drawing down the energy

00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:27.040
from the spinning turbine.

00:12:27.040 --> 00:12:29.590
And as a result, it
ran slower and slower,

00:12:29.590 --> 00:12:31.360
meaning that the
flow through the core

00:12:31.360 --> 00:12:36.100
was less and less, more water
boiled, going into steam,

00:12:36.100 --> 00:12:39.310
which increased the reactivity.

00:12:39.310 --> 00:12:43.210
As a result, the power
output of the court went up.

00:12:43.210 --> 00:12:44.830
It burned out more xenon.

00:12:44.830 --> 00:12:47.200
And the cycle continued.

00:12:47.200 --> 00:12:49.900
They noticed a power
excursion, about 40 seconds

00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:53.440
after they began the
test and at this point

00:12:53.440 --> 00:12:55.210
recognize they were
in bad territory

00:12:55.210 --> 00:12:57.430
and hit the scram button.

00:12:57.430 --> 00:13:00.220
This would jam pretty much all
of the available control rods

00:13:00.220 --> 00:13:02.530
into the core, including
some emergency extras,

00:13:02.530 --> 00:13:04.330
and shut everything down.

00:13:04.330 --> 00:13:07.060
In most circumstances, this
would be a fairly safe move.

00:13:07.060 --> 00:13:11.830
But in the case of the RBMK
it was most certainly not.

00:13:11.830 --> 00:13:16.150
RBMK control rods have
a graphite tip on them.

00:13:16.150 --> 00:13:19.570
When jammed into the core,
they caused a localized power

00:13:19.570 --> 00:13:22.990
increase because the graphite
is a great moderator.

00:13:22.990 --> 00:13:26.055
And it is displacing water,
which is a great absorber.

00:13:26.055 --> 00:13:28.180
And as a result, after they
made it a couple meters

00:13:28.180 --> 00:13:32.260
into the core, the
increased pressure

00:13:32.260 --> 00:13:36.280
in the core from the
power output, which

00:13:36.280 --> 00:13:38.530
was localized around the
tips the control rods,

00:13:38.530 --> 00:13:42.490
ended up shattering the
control rod drive mechanisms.

00:13:42.490 --> 00:13:47.290
And instead of turning off, the
cycle basically just continued,

00:13:47.290 --> 00:13:49.990
power continued to ramp up over
the next couple of seconds.

00:13:49.990 --> 00:13:52.630
It eventually reached
somewhere around 10 to 20

00:13:52.630 --> 00:13:55.720
times the maximum rated
thermal output of the system.

00:13:55.720 --> 00:13:57.490
And a massive steam
explosion ended up

00:13:57.490 --> 00:13:59.800
ripping through the facility.

00:13:59.800 --> 00:14:03.310
It tossed the 2000
ton biological shield

00:14:03.310 --> 00:14:07.150
on top of the reactor through
the roof of the facility.

00:14:07.150 --> 00:14:09.970
It injected a significant
portion of the fuel,

00:14:09.970 --> 00:14:12.460
as well as the
moderator in the core.

00:14:12.460 --> 00:14:15.717
And it started a massive
fire around the facility.

00:14:18.200 --> 00:14:19.825
Just to give you a
good sense of scale,

00:14:19.825 --> 00:14:22.810
let's see, if I've got
the virtual laser pointer.

00:14:22.810 --> 00:14:27.040
That's a person right
here, this little guy.

00:14:27.040 --> 00:14:29.980
This is the top of
the biological shield,

00:14:29.980 --> 00:14:32.380
Elena shield.

00:14:32.380 --> 00:14:37.420
And then this is a model, a
cutaway model of the Chernobyl

00:14:37.420 --> 00:14:41.410
reactor facility
with the shield,

00:14:41.410 --> 00:14:46.140
and with the flipped shield
that went up through the roof

00:14:46.140 --> 00:14:47.760
and came back down.

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:50.780
So as you can see, it was an
utterly massive explosion.

00:14:53.860 --> 00:14:58.480
So the damage to the reactor was
immediately quite catastrophic.

00:14:58.480 --> 00:15:00.340
Moderator blocks,
fuel was spread

00:15:00.340 --> 00:15:02.290
all around the immediate area.

00:15:02.290 --> 00:15:04.910
If you look in this photo,
it's rather difficult to see.

00:15:04.910 --> 00:15:07.330
But at the bottom of
that column of smoke

00:15:07.330 --> 00:15:11.410
you can actually see the bottom
up the biological shield.

00:15:11.410 --> 00:15:13.660
Kind of gives you a
sense of the scale

00:15:13.660 --> 00:15:15.840
of the damage to the reactor.

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:18.340
After the explosion happened,
actually none of the operators

00:15:18.340 --> 00:15:21.713
believe the reactor breached
confinement in any way.

00:15:21.713 --> 00:15:23.380
They didn't really
have an immediate way

00:15:23.380 --> 00:15:25.120
of seeing what had happened.

00:15:25.120 --> 00:15:27.580
So they open the door and went
to the main turbo generator

00:15:27.580 --> 00:15:29.320
building to
investigate the damage.

00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:32.590
They believed it was perhaps one
or two ruptured fuel channels.

00:15:32.590 --> 00:15:34.683
As it happened at, I
believe the Leningrad,

00:15:34.683 --> 00:15:36.100
I think it was the
Leningrad power

00:15:36.100 --> 00:15:38.333
station a few years earlier.

00:15:38.333 --> 00:15:40.000
In the few seconds
that they were there,

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.760
they received fatal doses
and died in the hospital

00:15:42.760 --> 00:15:45.040
in May of 1986.

00:15:45.040 --> 00:15:48.040
This is a photo from
control room of reactor 4,

00:15:48.040 --> 00:15:51.760
showing a jammed control rod
drive at the 6 meter position.

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:54.520
So this was probably
a rod, let's see,

00:15:54.520 --> 00:16:00.340
this is probably a rod coming
up from the bottom, in that it,

00:16:00.340 --> 00:16:02.020
seven meters would
be all the way out.

00:16:02.020 --> 00:16:03.520
Zero meters would
be all the way in.

00:16:07.010 --> 00:16:09.230
The initial response to
this, despite the fact

00:16:09.230 --> 00:16:11.780
that the reactor
operators were not

00:16:11.780 --> 00:16:13.610
yet dead, did
realize that it was

00:16:13.610 --> 00:16:15.500
a full breach of
containment, was

00:16:15.500 --> 00:16:18.300
the response was to an accident
that was non-nuclear in nature.

00:16:18.300 --> 00:16:21.740
So when the fire department
got a call from the authority

00:16:21.740 --> 00:16:25.580
at Chernobyl, the message
that they received

00:16:25.580 --> 00:16:28.490
was there's a fire at
the reactor complex.

00:16:28.490 --> 00:16:31.400
As a result, what
they showed up with

00:16:31.400 --> 00:16:38.510
was not equipment suitable for
a hazmat situation in any way.

00:16:38.510 --> 00:16:40.160
That said, there's
pretty much nothing

00:16:40.160 --> 00:16:43.778
that could shield anyone from
the extremely high radiation

00:16:43.778 --> 00:16:45.320
field that one would
encounter around

00:16:45.320 --> 00:16:47.820
the reactor in the immediate
aftermath of the accident.

00:16:47.820 --> 00:16:54.200
But nonetheless, they
were extremely vulnerable.

00:16:54.200 --> 00:16:56.240
It was night when this
accident happened.

00:16:56.240 --> 00:16:59.870
As I mentioned, this happened
at 1:23 in the morning.

00:16:59.870 --> 00:17:02.960
They actually couldn't see
the extent of the accident.

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:05.060
And they initially
believed that it was just

00:17:05.060 --> 00:17:07.585
a fire on the roof of the
turbo generator building.

00:17:07.585 --> 00:17:08.960
They attempted to
fight the fire.

00:17:08.960 --> 00:17:10.619
And some of them
actually succumb

00:17:10.619 --> 00:17:14.000
to acute radiation poisoning,
or acute radiation syndrome,

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.910
almost immediately.

00:17:16.910 --> 00:17:18.810
A number of firefighters
went up on the roof

00:17:18.810 --> 00:17:19.893
and just didn't come back.

00:17:24.400 --> 00:17:26.589
The aftermath of the
accident, the cleanup

00:17:26.589 --> 00:17:29.380
was handled by the Soviet Army.

00:17:29.380 --> 00:17:31.330
The people that were
involved in this

00:17:31.330 --> 00:17:33.910
were known as the liquidators.

00:17:33.910 --> 00:17:37.450
They would spend several minutes
on the rooftop of the turbo

00:17:37.450 --> 00:17:40.840
generator building, or up
near where the reactor was,

00:17:40.840 --> 00:17:42.730
the reactor containment
building was.

00:17:42.730 --> 00:17:48.440
And they would receive a,
effectively a lifetime dose,

00:17:48.440 --> 00:17:52.750
which I believe was, I believe
their limit was 50 REM.

00:17:52.750 --> 00:17:56.230
And that would be a couple
of minutes up there.

00:17:56.230 --> 00:18:01.060
Let's see, this photo doesn't
show much evidence of it.

00:18:01.060 --> 00:18:03.498
But I suppose it shows a
little bit of evidence of it.

00:18:03.498 --> 00:18:05.290
If you look around the
bottom up the frame,

00:18:05.290 --> 00:18:06.970
you can actually
see a little bit

00:18:06.970 --> 00:18:09.310
of hazing in kind of
a periodic fashion.

00:18:09.310 --> 00:18:15.440
Let's see if I can get my
pointer on it here, here, here,

00:18:15.440 --> 00:18:16.570
here, and here.

00:18:16.570 --> 00:18:19.810
That's the gear that
moves the film is actually

00:18:19.810 --> 00:18:23.590
shielding the film
from radiation

00:18:23.590 --> 00:18:25.360
exposure at those points.

00:18:25.360 --> 00:18:27.880
The radiation dose rate
was so high up there

00:18:27.880 --> 00:18:30.070
that most of the pictures
that were taken just

00:18:30.070 --> 00:18:32.590
didn't turn out whatsoever.

00:18:32.590 --> 00:18:36.160
A few smarter photographers
used a whole lot of lead

00:18:36.160 --> 00:18:38.060
and were able to capture
photos like this.

00:18:38.060 --> 00:18:40.990
But nonetheless, the dose
rates were tremendous.

00:18:43.940 --> 00:18:47.780
The reactor structure itself
was entombed in this thing

00:18:47.780 --> 00:18:50.000
that we call the sarcophagus.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:51.940
People in Ukraine call
it the object shelter,

00:18:51.940 --> 00:18:53.330
or the shelter object.

00:18:53.330 --> 00:18:56.810
It was constructed in
starting almost immediately

00:18:56.810 --> 00:19:01.790
after the accident, basically
to keep radioactive graphite

00:19:01.790 --> 00:19:05.300
and fuel fragments from
leaving the reactor structure

00:19:05.300 --> 00:19:07.800
and contaminating any more land.

00:19:07.800 --> 00:19:11.750
This is a photo from when
it was under construction.

00:19:11.750 --> 00:19:15.080
Basically what it consisted of
were steel and concrete walls

00:19:15.080 --> 00:19:18.290
that were erected
around the reactor,

00:19:18.290 --> 00:19:20.360
using a variety of technologies.

00:19:20.360 --> 00:19:24.290
They at first attempted
to use robots,

00:19:24.290 --> 00:19:27.860
that were almost
immediately rendered useless

00:19:27.860 --> 00:19:30.350
by the high radiation field.

00:19:30.350 --> 00:19:35.000
Later on, they ended up using
quote "bio robots," people,

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:38.720
to move things into place.

00:19:38.720 --> 00:19:40.820
As I've said before,
a whole lot of people

00:19:40.820 --> 00:19:46.250
died in this accident both
immediately and after,

00:19:46.250 --> 00:19:49.550
many during the construction
of the sarcophagus.

00:19:49.550 --> 00:19:51.560
Actually during the
initial firefighting,

00:19:51.560 --> 00:19:53.930
or yeah, the initial
firefighting measures,

00:19:53.930 --> 00:19:56.780
as the core remained burning
for a number of weeks

00:19:56.780 --> 00:20:00.470
after the accident,
they attempted

00:20:00.470 --> 00:20:04.610
to put it out with bags of
sand dropped from helicopters.

00:20:04.610 --> 00:20:08.090
And during that effort,
a helicopter actually

00:20:08.090 --> 00:20:09.680
ended up hitting
one of the cranes

00:20:09.680 --> 00:20:11.600
that they were attempting
to use for this

00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:14.360
and falling into the
reactor, and a good portion

00:20:14.360 --> 00:20:17.390
of its remains remain entombed
within the sarcophagus,

00:20:17.390 --> 00:20:21.130
from what I understand.

00:20:21.130 --> 00:20:24.710
All right, so my visit to
Chernobyl, why would anyone

00:20:24.710 --> 00:20:26.360
ever want to go there?

00:20:26.360 --> 00:20:27.980
The primary focus
was to learn about

00:20:27.980 --> 00:20:31.220
radiological
decontamination at the site,

00:20:31.220 --> 00:20:34.250
basically how is
contamination control managed,

00:20:34.250 --> 00:20:35.588
how do workers stay safe.

00:20:35.588 --> 00:20:37.130
Mind you, there are
3,000 people that

00:20:37.130 --> 00:20:40.160
go to work there every day.

00:20:40.160 --> 00:20:41.630
And what are the strengths?

00:20:41.630 --> 00:20:44.495
And what are the shortcomings
of their radiological program?

00:20:44.495 --> 00:20:49.010
It was seven days total,
four of which were on site.

00:20:49.010 --> 00:20:52.970
Other days were spent
in Pripyat as well as

00:20:52.970 --> 00:20:57.320
in some classroom training,
which I've got great photos of.

00:20:57.320 --> 00:21:00.260
So this is a slide stolen
directly from the PowerPoint

00:21:00.260 --> 00:21:02.730
that I was sent on day one.

00:21:02.730 --> 00:21:06.650
But this was organized by
three people, Carl Willis,

00:21:06.650 --> 00:21:08.810
Erik Kambarian, and Ed Geist.

00:21:08.810 --> 00:21:10.400
I've known Carl for
a few years now.

00:21:10.400 --> 00:21:13.070
He lives in
Albuquerque, New Mexico

00:21:13.070 --> 00:21:15.530
and is a radiation safety
officer at a company

00:21:15.530 --> 00:21:20.030
that, I think they do advanced
energy storage technologies.

00:21:20.030 --> 00:21:22.070
I'm not exactly sure.

