00:22:42.690 --> 00:22:44.760
wearing those absurd
robes before we

00:22:44.760 --> 00:22:48.060
were going to go
in to another room

00:22:48.060 --> 00:22:52.350
and change into basically
coveralls, which

00:22:52.350 --> 00:22:55.295
are easy to decontaminate.

00:22:55.295 --> 00:22:56.670
One of the activities
that we did

00:22:56.670 --> 00:22:58.890
was real decontamination
training.

00:22:58.890 --> 00:23:02.610
So that is a truck from
the Novarka work site,

00:23:02.610 --> 00:23:06.300
which, by the way, that is
me with a Geiger counter.

00:23:06.300 --> 00:23:08.970
I'm surveying for contamination.

00:23:08.970 --> 00:23:11.357
We then pressure
washed the truck.

00:23:11.357 --> 00:23:13.440
As it turns out, there's
a very specific technique

00:23:13.440 --> 00:23:15.815
one needs to use for pressure
washing when you're dealing

00:23:15.815 --> 00:23:19.650
with a contaminated object, so
as to not blast contaminated

00:23:19.650 --> 00:23:22.180
dirt up back onto the truck.

00:23:22.180 --> 00:23:24.480
This was a very interesting
experience and also

00:23:24.480 --> 00:23:27.120
one that was very entertaining
for the workers involved,

00:23:27.120 --> 00:23:30.300
because they don't actually
wear that when they're

00:23:30.300 --> 00:23:35.100
doing decontamination because
their respect for safety

00:23:35.100 --> 00:23:38.220
protocols are, shall we
say, a bit different.

00:23:38.220 --> 00:23:40.950
So they got to see us
where the absurd rubber

00:23:40.950 --> 00:23:46.890
ducky suits while they stood
by smoking and laughing at us.

00:23:46.890 --> 00:23:49.810
I believe you can actually see
the corner of that guy's jacket

00:23:49.810 --> 00:23:50.310
back there.

00:23:50.310 --> 00:23:52.860
And he's just wearing
everyday clothes.

00:23:55.700 --> 00:23:58.640
We also went on the new
safe confinement work site.

00:23:58.640 --> 00:24:01.160
So I haven't talked about it
earlier in this presentation,

00:24:01.160 --> 00:24:03.440
but I suppose I should have.

00:24:03.440 --> 00:24:07.640
There is a object called
the New Safe Confinement

00:24:07.640 --> 00:24:12.890
Arch that consists of basically
a giant stainless steel

00:24:12.890 --> 00:24:16.940
structure on rails which is
being slid over reactor 4

00:24:16.940 --> 00:24:19.490
so as to prevent the spread
of any sort of contamination

00:24:19.490 --> 00:24:20.780
from it.

00:24:20.780 --> 00:24:25.550
This is known as the New Safe
Confinement, or NSC, arch.

00:24:25.550 --> 00:24:28.430
It's been under
construction since 2007.

00:24:28.430 --> 00:24:31.580
And it just moved
for the first time,

00:24:31.580 --> 00:24:36.860
actually while I was there,
so on the 12th of November.

00:24:36.860 --> 00:24:40.940
It's supposed to
last for 100 years.

00:24:40.940 --> 00:24:42.830
And hopefully in that
kind of time span

00:24:42.830 --> 00:24:46.430
they'll be able to take apart
what remains of the reactor.

00:24:46.430 --> 00:24:51.770
So actually what you see here is
the corner of the sarcophagus.

00:24:51.770 --> 00:24:55.430
And then if you were to pan
over this way a little bit,

00:24:55.430 --> 00:25:00.350
you'd see the right set
of tracks for the New Safe

00:25:00.350 --> 00:25:03.040
Confinement Arch.

00:25:03.040 --> 00:25:05.803
We also did some
classroom training.

00:25:05.803 --> 00:25:07.220
Admittedly, the
classroom training

00:25:07.220 --> 00:25:10.490
was the most disappointing
part of this.

00:25:10.490 --> 00:25:13.130
The instructors were
not particularly

00:25:13.130 --> 00:25:15.740
interested in showing
us really anything

00:25:15.740 --> 00:25:21.380
other than YouTube videos and
other things that would just

00:25:21.380 --> 00:25:22.760
waste our time.

00:25:22.760 --> 00:25:26.267
That was the one part of this
trip that I did not enjoy.

00:25:26.267 --> 00:25:28.100
Regardless, we did get
to learn a little bit

00:25:28.100 --> 00:25:32.240
about the various hazmat
getups that folks would

00:25:32.240 --> 00:25:36.280
wear when working on site.

00:25:36.280 --> 00:25:41.050
As I mentioned we also
got to visit Pripyat,

00:25:41.050 --> 00:25:43.090
which I have more
photos of later,

00:25:43.090 --> 00:25:45.970
as well as the reactor
4 control room, which

00:25:45.970 --> 00:25:50.290
is inside the sarcophagus,
which is quite a treat to visit.

00:25:50.290 --> 00:25:52.870
The reactor 4
control room is not

00:25:52.870 --> 00:25:56.080
terribly contaminated as a
result of the decontamination

00:25:56.080 --> 00:25:57.190
efforts.

00:25:57.190 --> 00:25:59.050
During the accident,
the dose rate

00:25:59.050 --> 00:26:03.100
would have been somewhere in the
range of 5 to 10 rem an hour.

00:26:03.100 --> 00:26:06.580
But today, it's in the
range of 10 mrem an hour.

