00:26:39.355 --> 00:26:41.230
Remember that long
building that I showed you

00:26:41.230 --> 00:26:44.980
that connected reactors
1 and 2 and 3 and 4?

00:26:44.980 --> 00:26:47.530
This is right outside
the reactor 3 part of it.

00:26:47.530 --> 00:26:50.680
There are-- I think I'll
show you these photos later.

00:26:50.680 --> 00:26:55.870
There are chunks of the
turbine from reactor 4

00:26:55.870 --> 00:27:01.090
that are down here in this
area that are quite visibly

00:27:01.090 --> 00:27:05.080
radioactive and are very easy
to detect if one swings a Geiger

00:27:05.080 --> 00:27:06.340
counter about.

00:27:06.340 --> 00:27:10.490
Within Pripyat we also
visited a hospital 126,

00:27:10.490 --> 00:27:12.970
which is where the
firefighters went immediately

00:27:12.970 --> 00:27:18.010
after the accident, that is, the
ones that made it off the roof.

00:27:18.010 --> 00:27:21.352
This garment here,
we're not exactly

00:27:21.352 --> 00:27:22.810
sure what it was
because none of us

00:27:22.810 --> 00:27:24.130
were going to really touch it.

00:27:24.130 --> 00:27:27.250
But we think it might have
been part of a cover--

00:27:27.250 --> 00:27:28.720
it would go under one's helmet--

00:27:28.720 --> 00:27:31.120
was extremely radioactive.

00:27:31.120 --> 00:27:34.680
It was contaminated with
alpha, beta, and gamma,

00:27:34.680 --> 00:27:35.680
which is fairly unusual.

00:27:35.680 --> 00:27:39.550
Alpha contamination is fairly
rare around the Chernobyl site,

00:27:39.550 --> 00:27:43.390
and was somewhere around 50
to 75 mR an hour on contact.

