00:29:29.910 --> 00:29:32.280
All right, so this is our
excursion into Pripyat

00:29:32.280 --> 00:29:33.990
on our second day.

00:29:33.990 --> 00:29:37.020
So this is the group
led by Stanislaus.

00:29:37.020 --> 00:29:40.500
As you can see, there's
not very much left.

00:29:40.500 --> 00:29:42.780
Just in comparison to
what we saw last year,

00:29:42.780 --> 00:29:45.990
the number of buildings
that had been taken apart

00:29:45.990 --> 00:29:51.210
for scrap metal, illegally,
of course, was pretty huge.

00:29:51.210 --> 00:29:52.925
In, I don't know,
5 or 10 years, it's

00:29:52.925 --> 00:29:55.300
going to be very difficult to
see much of Pripyat at all,

00:29:55.300 --> 00:29:56.850
frankly.

00:29:56.850 --> 00:30:00.210
So this is a standard
apartment block in Pripyat.

00:30:00.210 --> 00:30:03.180
As you can see, a lot
of broken windows.

00:30:03.180 --> 00:30:04.793
A lot of bricks have fallen off.

00:30:04.793 --> 00:30:06.210
These things are
pretty dangerous.

00:30:06.210 --> 00:30:07.950
A lot of tourists
do go into them.

00:30:07.950 --> 00:30:11.060
If one decides to do a tourist
expedition to Chernobyl-- which

00:30:11.060 --> 00:30:13.290
I don't particularly
recommend-- don't

00:30:13.290 --> 00:30:14.415
go in the apartment blocks.

00:30:17.370 --> 00:30:20.370
This is on the way to
one of the schools.

00:30:20.370 --> 00:30:24.250
This is Lucas who has more
detectors than anyone I've ever

00:30:24.250 --> 00:30:24.750
met.

00:30:24.750 --> 00:30:26.710
He was wearing 7 at the time.

00:30:26.710 --> 00:30:29.340
So I had to take a photo of him.

00:30:29.340 --> 00:30:32.040
This is Iris imitating
some of the graffiti, which

00:30:32.040 --> 00:30:34.830
unfortunately has popped
up all over the place.

00:30:34.830 --> 00:30:38.230
Pripyat itself is
really decaying quickly.

00:30:38.230 --> 00:30:42.180
As I've said, there's a
huge problem with looting.

00:30:42.180 --> 00:30:43.680
In addition, there's
a huge problem

00:30:43.680 --> 00:30:46.230
with graffiti and vandalism.

00:30:46.230 --> 00:30:48.330
It's really
depressing, honestly,

00:30:48.330 --> 00:30:54.090
to go there and see how much
has changed just in a year.

00:30:54.090 --> 00:30:55.920
So despite my
earlier warning, we

00:30:55.920 --> 00:30:57.150
did go in an apartment block.

00:31:01.830 --> 00:31:03.780
This is just a
measurement showing

00:31:03.780 --> 00:31:06.570
that the background up there
actually is not terribly high.

00:31:09.330 --> 00:31:13.240
Yeah, that's Iris, not
particularly safety conscious

00:31:13.240 --> 00:31:15.960
at times.

00:31:15.960 --> 00:31:17.710
This gives you a good
idea of how far away

00:31:17.710 --> 00:31:19.233
Pripyat is from the reactor.

00:31:19.233 --> 00:31:21.025
That is not very far,
about two kilometers.

00:31:21.025 --> 00:31:23.050
So you can see the New
Safe Confinement Arch

00:31:23.050 --> 00:31:26.650
to the top left of the detector.

00:31:26.650 --> 00:31:29.650
Background there is about,
in this particular apartment

00:31:29.650 --> 00:31:32.530
block, at this particular
time, was about four to five

00:31:32.530 --> 00:31:36.292
times what you would see
in downtown Cambridge.

00:31:39.740 --> 00:31:42.000
There are wild
animals in Pripyat

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:44.160
and the rest of
the exclusion zone.

00:31:44.160 --> 00:31:45.570
This is a huge problem.

00:31:45.570 --> 00:31:48.300
So despite the fact that
the cats are very cute

00:31:48.300 --> 00:31:51.770
and the puppies are very
cute, they also have rabies,

00:31:51.770 --> 00:31:54.630
not all of them, but a
very large number of them.

00:31:54.630 --> 00:31:58.140
In 2009, five workers were
injured by, I kid you not,

00:31:58.140 --> 00:31:59.412
a rabid wolf.

00:31:59.412 --> 00:32:00.870
There's a YouTube
video of this you

00:32:00.870 --> 00:32:04.320
can look up on your own
time if you so wish.

00:32:04.320 --> 00:32:07.300
This is because Ukraine
doesn't have a lot of money.

00:32:07.300 --> 00:32:11.320
So they have not been able to
continue with their vaccination

00:32:11.320 --> 00:32:11.820
program.

00:32:11.820 --> 00:32:17.700
They actually use baits that
have a rabies vaccine in them

00:32:17.700 --> 00:32:22.290
to normally suppress rabies
in wild animal populations.

00:32:22.290 --> 00:32:23.820
But Ukraine doesn't
have any money.

00:32:23.820 --> 00:32:26.410
They killed the program
about five years ago.

00:32:26.410 --> 00:32:29.220
And as a result there's a
huge, huge problem with,

00:32:29.220 --> 00:32:30.870
especially rabid foxes.

00:32:30.870 --> 00:32:36.360
Because everyone thinks foxes
are cute, especially tourists.

00:32:36.360 --> 00:32:38.700
And foxes, when they
get rabies, some of them

00:32:38.700 --> 00:32:41.400
go through a stage in which
they appear to be very friendly.

00:32:41.400 --> 00:32:43.230
As far as I know,
no one has gotten

00:32:43.230 --> 00:32:46.770
rabies from a rabid
animal at Chernobyl.

00:32:46.770 --> 00:32:50.250
But it's certainly
a possibility.

00:32:50.250 --> 00:32:54.540
So Stanislaus was being a very
bad example by feeding one

00:32:54.540 --> 00:32:57.480
of the wild cats.

00:32:57.480 --> 00:33:00.425
So that's why I took
a picture of it.

00:33:00.425 --> 00:33:01.800
This is one of
the many memorials

00:33:01.800 --> 00:33:03.450
that you'll find in
downtown Slavutych.

00:33:03.450 --> 00:33:05.880
We stayed in the city that
was built, effectively,

00:33:05.880 --> 00:33:07.530
as a replacement for Pripyat.

00:33:07.530 --> 00:33:09.660
It's actually a fantastic town.

00:33:09.660 --> 00:33:12.900
I really enjoy Slavutych.

00:33:12.900 --> 00:33:15.780
And as one might expect,
there are memorials

00:33:15.780 --> 00:33:18.810
everywhere because the entire
population is basically

00:33:18.810 --> 00:33:24.060
the folks that were removed
from the town of Pripyat.

00:33:24.060 --> 00:33:26.700
This is the train we
would take every day.

00:33:26.700 --> 00:33:30.750
Slavutych is
separated from Pripyat

00:33:30.750 --> 00:33:34.240
by a little isthmus of
Belarus that drops down.

00:33:34.240 --> 00:33:38.040
So that's bad, because you
can't get a visa to Belarus.

00:33:38.040 --> 00:33:41.240
It's not really a thing
you can do as an American.

00:33:41.240 --> 00:33:42.490
I mean, you can apply for one.

00:33:42.490 --> 00:33:44.310
You'll just never hear back.

00:33:44.310 --> 00:33:46.710
Belarus is Europe's
last dictatorship.

00:33:46.710 --> 00:33:50.830
And it's not some place one
wants to go for any reason.

00:33:50.830 --> 00:33:54.267
So when we would get on this
train, the doors would shut.

00:33:54.267 --> 00:33:56.100
We would go through
Belarus and we would all

00:33:56.100 --> 00:33:58.535
pray that didn't break
down because then we

00:33:58.535 --> 00:34:00.660
would have to spend some
time to Belarus in prison.

00:34:00.660 --> 00:34:02.790
But yeah, this is the train
yard, bright and early.

00:34:06.560 --> 00:34:10.130
The various zones on the
reactor site for cleanliness,

00:34:10.130 --> 00:34:11.929
so to speak,
radiological cleanliness

00:34:11.929 --> 00:34:15.325
are separated by these
benches effectively,

00:34:15.325 --> 00:34:18.409
that you have to step over, so
that it reminds you that, hey,

00:34:18.409 --> 00:34:20.120
this is the clean area.

00:34:20.120 --> 00:34:23.330
You need to be wearing
boot covers and at least

00:34:23.330 --> 00:34:24.800
these garments in
order to go here.

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:32.745
Sideways, for some reason,
this is part of the--

00:34:32.745 --> 00:34:34.870
all right, I don't know
why these are all sideways.

00:34:34.870 --> 00:34:37.810
But regardless, you
get the picture.

00:34:37.810 --> 00:34:40.030
If you notice on the
top of the screen, which

00:34:40.030 --> 00:34:41.409
should be the left
of the screen,

00:34:41.409 --> 00:34:43.120
let's see if I can rotate it.

00:34:46.150 --> 00:34:48.130
That's a giant puddle of water.

00:34:48.130 --> 00:34:49.929
This place is falling apart.

00:34:49.929 --> 00:34:51.520
Despite the fact
that they have money

00:34:51.520 --> 00:34:56.139
from the European bank on
reconstruction and development

00:34:56.139 --> 00:34:57.970
for the New Safe
Confinement Arch,

00:34:57.970 --> 00:35:01.760
the Chernobyl site itself
does not have a lot of money.

00:35:01.760 --> 00:35:04.210
And as a result things
are falling apart.

00:35:04.210 --> 00:35:05.710
And the amount of
contamination that

00:35:05.710 --> 00:35:08.290
is getting into places where
it very much shouldn't be,

00:35:08.290 --> 00:35:11.290
like this quote "clean
area," is fairly high.

00:35:11.290 --> 00:35:14.300
That puddle of water was pretty
toasty, something like 5 to 8

00:35:14.300 --> 00:35:17.670
mR an hour on contact.

00:35:17.670 --> 00:35:19.060
That's generally quite bad.

00:35:22.400 --> 00:35:24.140
As I said, water is
coming in everywhere.

00:35:24.140 --> 00:35:28.480
And in this case they were using
leg covers to catch the water.

00:35:31.578 --> 00:35:33.870
Another one of the hallways
that had water leak into it

00:35:33.870 --> 00:35:36.976
and therefore all
the lights are out.

00:35:36.976 --> 00:35:39.170
That's the footwear
which we were issued,

00:35:39.170 --> 00:35:43.030
which breaks after walking
about a kilometer, which is not

00:35:43.030 --> 00:35:47.440
particularly encouraging if one
wants to take their boots back.

00:35:47.440 --> 00:35:49.750
Again, walking down
the hallway, you

00:35:49.750 --> 00:35:51.760
notice this gold
corrugated material

00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:53.680
that you see on the sides?

00:35:53.680 --> 00:35:56.350
It's aluminum that is anodized.

00:35:56.350 --> 00:35:58.150
And it's placed there
because it covers up

00:35:58.150 --> 00:36:02.350
all of the sheets of lead
that were affixed to the wall.

00:36:02.350 --> 00:36:05.680
What happened is in the
aftermath of the accident,

00:36:05.680 --> 00:36:08.710
the entire facility was just
hopelessly contaminated.

00:36:08.710 --> 00:36:11.860
And you can scrub all you
want, but ultimately it's

00:36:11.860 --> 00:36:14.500
very difficult to get
radioactive contamination off

00:36:14.500 --> 00:36:15.360
of things.

00:36:15.360 --> 00:36:17.110
So what they ended up
doing was getting it

00:36:17.110 --> 00:36:19.300
down to a somewhat
acceptable level,

00:36:19.300 --> 00:36:21.460
and then fastening
sheets of lead over it,

00:36:21.460 --> 00:36:24.520
and then fastening this
stuff over the top of that.

00:36:27.510 --> 00:36:29.160
This is unit 2's control room.

00:36:29.160 --> 00:36:31.260
So this is what a fully
fleshed-out control

00:36:31.260 --> 00:36:32.010
room looks like.

00:36:35.010 --> 00:36:38.940
Unit 2 were shut down in 2000.

00:36:38.940 --> 00:36:41.160
The reactors actually
continued operating

00:36:41.160 --> 00:36:44.070
after the 1986
Chernobyl accident

00:36:44.070 --> 00:36:47.580
because Ukraine was in such
desperate need of power.

00:36:47.580 --> 00:36:50.730
As a result, the fuel
is still fairly hot.

00:36:50.730 --> 00:36:53.640
It's producing a reasonable
amount of decay heat.

00:36:53.640 --> 00:36:57.120
And there is a crew that
sits in the control room

00:36:57.120 --> 00:37:00.440
at all times monitoring it.

00:37:00.440 --> 00:37:03.000
That's Nathan.

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:04.750
This is actually, I
took a picture of this

00:37:04.750 --> 00:37:08.230
because it's a very good
diagram of the Chernobyl reactor

00:37:08.230 --> 00:37:10.570
that's simplified.

00:37:10.570 --> 00:37:13.750
It shows the core and
the relative locations

00:37:13.750 --> 00:37:19.260
of these steam,
water separators.

00:37:19.260 --> 00:37:23.870
OK, as I said, there is a
team that stays in there.

00:37:23.870 --> 00:37:27.670
So there are people that work
on site and work in the reactor

00:37:27.670 --> 00:37:29.980
control rooms, which
I have to imagine

00:37:29.980 --> 00:37:34.040
has to be a bit
of a surreal job.

00:37:34.040 --> 00:37:40.340
This is inside the main, inside
the turbo generator hall.

00:37:40.340 --> 00:37:46.970
Those chunks that you see here
are from the turbo generator

00:37:46.970 --> 00:37:49.370
of reactor 4.

00:37:49.370 --> 00:37:52.370
So they're quite contaminated
and quite easy to detect.

00:37:52.370 --> 00:37:54.620
Actually, there is a
good story behind this.

00:37:54.620 --> 00:37:58.370
So we were trying to
figure out exactly what was

00:37:58.370 --> 00:38:02.930
making the dose rate so high in
the area when we were up there.

00:38:02.930 --> 00:38:07.170
So we got a group of us to stand
in a circle, minus one person.

00:38:07.170 --> 00:38:08.060
So there's a gap.

00:38:08.060 --> 00:38:10.780
We got a person in the
center with a scintillator.

00:38:10.780 --> 00:38:12.860
And we all kind
of rotated around

00:38:12.860 --> 00:38:14.422
until we found in
which direction

00:38:14.422 --> 00:38:16.880
the scintillator reading was
high enough, so basically made

00:38:16.880 --> 00:38:20.180
like a 2 pi meat shield.

00:38:20.180 --> 00:38:21.350
It worked fairly well.

00:38:21.350 --> 00:38:25.170
It thoroughly baffled all of
the guides that were with us.

00:38:25.170 --> 00:38:27.920
They were like, what are
you doing linking arms

00:38:27.920 --> 00:38:29.900
and spinning around.

00:38:29.900 --> 00:38:32.240
Regardless, that is a
good way to find sources

00:38:32.240 --> 00:38:33.230
if you're in a pinch.

00:38:35.790 --> 00:38:37.410
This is looking
the other direction

00:38:37.410 --> 00:38:41.250
from that same vantage
point as in the last photo.

00:38:41.250 --> 00:38:44.010
Behind those walls with a
little radiation signs on them

00:38:44.010 --> 00:38:49.440
are chunks of the ventilation
stack, which is fairly iconic.

00:38:49.440 --> 00:38:51.870
They've been fairly
well decontaminated.

00:38:51.870 --> 00:38:56.040
At that fence area, the
dose rate or more accurately

00:38:56.040 --> 00:39:00.030
exposure rate,
was 10 mR an hour.

00:39:00.030 --> 00:39:02.760
And yeah, that's another
close up photo of it.

00:39:02.760 --> 00:39:05.670
And I managed to sneak by
phone over the top of it

00:39:05.670 --> 00:39:07.050
and get a good shot.

00:39:07.050 --> 00:39:09.210
Unfortunately, none of
the pieces are uncovered.

00:39:09.210 --> 00:39:12.060
I would really like to
see the orange and white

00:39:12.060 --> 00:39:14.490
of the ventilation stack.

00:39:14.490 --> 00:39:17.740
But I did not.

00:39:17.740 --> 00:39:19.740
Again, same shot,
slightly different

00:39:19.740 --> 00:39:22.140
shot of the turbo generator
hallway looking in the unit

00:39:22.140 --> 00:39:25.570
1 2 direction.

00:39:25.570 --> 00:39:33.380
More detritus, oh here's
a slightly better close

00:39:33.380 --> 00:39:35.672
up of those components.

00:39:38.020 --> 00:39:40.520
One of the interesting things
I found out about the facility

00:39:40.520 --> 00:39:42.480
is way that access
is controlled.

00:39:42.480 --> 00:39:46.110
So instead of having an RFID
card or something like that,

00:39:46.110 --> 00:39:47.940
they've got cameras
and operators.

00:39:47.940 --> 00:39:53.360
So what you see
here is a camera.

00:39:53.360 --> 00:39:57.500
So Stanislaus would scan a badge
that would automatically call

00:39:57.500 --> 00:40:00.020
someone who is an operator.

00:40:00.020 --> 00:40:02.270
Stanislaus would say,
hey, I'm at this door.

00:40:02.270 --> 00:40:04.938
I want to go into this location.

00:40:04.938 --> 00:40:05.730
Will you let me in?

00:40:05.730 --> 00:40:07.355
And then they would
look at the camera,

00:40:07.355 --> 00:40:09.500
determine that yes,
that is Stanislaus.

00:40:09.500 --> 00:40:11.545
He does want to
go into this area.

00:40:11.545 --> 00:40:13.670
And then they would approve
it and let him through.

00:40:17.010 --> 00:40:19.800
Walking through the
corridors of the sarcophagus.

00:40:19.800 --> 00:40:21.960
You can actually see up
here those lead sheets

00:40:21.960 --> 00:40:24.032
I was talking about.

00:40:24.032 --> 00:40:25.740
I don't know how thick
they are on there,

00:40:25.740 --> 00:40:28.110
or how close they are to
falling off, for that matter.

00:40:28.110 --> 00:40:31.170
But I'm sure several
thousand pounds of lead

00:40:31.170 --> 00:40:33.840
is right there alone.

00:40:33.840 --> 00:40:37.440
These are main circulating
pumps, about one-half

00:40:37.440 --> 00:40:43.080
of the main circulating
pumps for reactor 2.

00:40:43.080 --> 00:40:44.700
And each one of
these things takes

00:40:44.700 --> 00:40:47.970
something around, something
around 40 megawatts

00:40:47.970 --> 00:40:50.790
to actually operate.

00:40:50.790 --> 00:40:54.420
These are aligned
differently and are

00:40:54.420 --> 00:40:57.870
of a different type than
the ones used in reactor 4

00:40:57.870 --> 00:41:01.440
because reactors 1 and 2
were of an earlier design.

00:41:01.440 --> 00:41:03.930
Ironically enough,
reactors 1 and 2 actually

00:41:03.930 --> 00:41:05.700
don't have all of
the safety measures

00:41:05.700 --> 00:41:10.050
that reactor 4 does, which is
a bit terrifying to think of.

00:41:12.770 --> 00:41:18.260
Yet more photos, right, as I
said, dog problem at Chernobyl.

00:41:18.260 --> 00:41:20.960
This is right outside the
entrance to a clean facility.

00:41:20.960 --> 00:41:22.910
And occasionally these
dogs would wander in.

00:41:22.910 --> 00:41:27.500
Unfortunately dogs are large
furry piles of easily airborne

00:41:27.500 --> 00:41:28.800
contamination.

00:41:28.800 --> 00:41:30.710
So they would walk in.

00:41:30.710 --> 00:41:32.210
People would go
to shoo them out.

00:41:32.210 --> 00:41:33.980
They would shake their
coats or whatever.

00:41:33.980 --> 00:41:36.440
And then clean up
on aisle three,

00:41:36.440 --> 00:41:41.300
because now there's
contamination everywhere.

00:41:41.300 --> 00:41:44.330
More sad looking puppies.

00:41:44.330 --> 00:41:47.750
New Safe Confinement, yet again,
to give you an idea of scale,

00:41:47.750 --> 00:41:49.355
let's play find the workers.

00:42:06.560 --> 00:42:10.400
Those are workers right there.

00:42:10.400 --> 00:42:11.720
Can you guys see them?

00:42:11.720 --> 00:42:12.980
AUDIENCE: Barely.

00:42:12.980 --> 00:42:17.810
JAKE HECLA: Yeah, they're
really, really small

00:42:17.810 --> 00:42:20.324
next to this facility.

00:42:20.324 --> 00:42:22.280
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:22.280 --> 00:42:27.170
JAKE HECLA: Yeah, I think I've
got a slightly better shot

00:42:27.170 --> 00:42:27.670
here.

00:42:31.390 --> 00:42:33.970
That's a guy right there.

00:42:33.970 --> 00:42:37.550
There's also another
dude right here.

00:42:37.550 --> 00:42:40.300
Yeah, this place is,
or this structure

00:42:40.300 --> 00:42:41.343
is absolutely enormous.

00:42:41.343 --> 00:42:42.760
It's really hard
to wrap your head

00:42:42.760 --> 00:42:45.430
around exactly how large it is.

00:42:45.430 --> 00:42:49.117
So this is in an area
called the local zone.

00:42:49.117 --> 00:42:50.950
So it's the immediate
several hundred meters

00:42:50.950 --> 00:42:52.870
surrounding the reactor.

00:42:52.870 --> 00:42:54.612
As you can see, the
hazmat equipment

00:42:54.612 --> 00:42:56.320
that we're wearing
there is significantly

00:42:56.320 --> 00:42:58.700
different from what we would
wear inside the reactor

00:42:58.700 --> 00:43:00.880
or inside the
sarcophagus, mostly

00:43:00.880 --> 00:43:03.940
because the threat from dust
in this area is pretty huge.

00:43:07.510 --> 00:43:09.190
As you can see, we're
walking on fill.

00:43:09.190 --> 00:43:11.110
It's actually meters
and meters of fill

00:43:11.110 --> 00:43:12.820
because the ground
was so contaminated

00:43:12.820 --> 00:43:15.970
that they scraped it
away, put fill in there,

00:43:15.970 --> 00:43:19.120
put fill on top of that because
just the residual contamination

00:43:19.120 --> 00:43:22.180
was enough to make it hazardous
to use as a work site.

00:43:22.180 --> 00:43:24.820
Though they're not
shown in this image,

00:43:24.820 --> 00:43:29.105
or I believe any
images here, there

00:43:29.105 --> 00:43:31.480
are little concrete
and lead structures

00:43:31.480 --> 00:43:34.270
that these workers
take breaks behind

00:43:34.270 --> 00:43:38.500
because you have a dose
limit that is enforced

00:43:38.500 --> 00:43:39.910
while you're working there.

00:43:39.910 --> 00:43:41.620
And if you're going
to take a smoke

00:43:41.620 --> 00:43:44.110
break, as a huge fraction
of the population of Ukraine

00:43:44.110 --> 00:43:49.522
smokes, or you're going to
take a break of another sort,

00:43:49.522 --> 00:43:51.730
they don't want you racking
up dose during that time.

00:43:51.730 --> 00:43:54.400
So you basically hide in
a little concrete shack

00:43:54.400 --> 00:43:56.200
for a while with a
few inches of lead

00:43:56.200 --> 00:43:59.140
between you and the reactor.

00:43:59.140 --> 00:44:03.940
Yet another shot
inside the sarcophagus,

00:44:03.940 --> 00:44:06.710
Ed explaining something
about which I'm not sure.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:13.040
As you can see these
places are not exactly

00:44:13.040 --> 00:44:14.930
in the best condition
on the inside.

00:44:14.930 --> 00:44:16.820
And one thing that
did concern me a lot

00:44:16.820 --> 00:44:19.400
was the amount of dust
that was very, very

00:44:19.400 --> 00:44:21.920
easy to kick up in the area.

00:44:21.920 --> 00:44:26.290
This is inside control
room of reactor 4.

00:44:26.290 --> 00:44:29.260
Selfie, which I didn't
mean to have in this album.

00:44:33.460 --> 00:44:37.060
Control room 4 hasn't changed
a whole lot since last year.

00:44:37.060 --> 00:44:40.150
But there is a
dividing wall that

00:44:40.150 --> 00:44:42.520
actually separates
reactors 3 and 4 that's

00:44:42.520 --> 00:44:43.780
being put together.

00:44:43.780 --> 00:44:47.190
And it cuts right through the
edge of the fourth control

00:44:47.190 --> 00:44:47.690
room.

00:44:47.690 --> 00:44:50.685
And for a while, we actually
didn't know whether or not

00:44:50.685 --> 00:44:52.810
we were going to be able
to visit it at all because

00:44:52.810 --> 00:44:53.920
of ongoing construction.

00:44:53.920 --> 00:44:57.640
I'm very glad that
we were able to.

00:44:57.640 --> 00:45:00.280
Most of the instruments
have been removed.

00:45:00.280 --> 00:45:02.590
It's unclear as to why.

00:45:02.590 --> 00:45:05.350
We've been told that some of it
was because of contamination.

00:45:05.350 --> 00:45:09.160
But the pattern doesn't
really make sense.

00:45:09.160 --> 00:45:15.320
This is the reactor control
room cartogram, excuse me,

00:45:15.320 --> 00:45:17.480
reactor core cartogram,
which, as I said

00:45:17.480 --> 00:45:21.020
was lit and could display
various parameters regarding

00:45:21.020 --> 00:45:24.420
the various fuel channels.

00:45:24.420 --> 00:45:30.080
There is only two control
rod indicator, well, yeah.

00:45:30.080 --> 00:45:34.870
There are really only these
control rod indicators left.

00:45:34.870 --> 00:45:36.620
And we believe that
actually some of these

00:45:36.620 --> 00:45:37.580
might not be original.

00:45:37.580 --> 00:45:39.163
Someone might have
stolen the real one

00:45:39.163 --> 00:45:42.493
and put another one back.

00:45:42.493 --> 00:45:44.160
I don't have any
evidence to support it.

00:45:44.160 --> 00:45:45.980
But I suspect that there's
significant looting that

00:45:45.980 --> 00:45:46.647
happens in here.

00:45:51.970 --> 00:45:54.370
This is a rather
entertaining photo.

00:45:54.370 --> 00:45:57.760
That means smoking area.

00:45:57.760 --> 00:45:59.048
That's in the control room.

00:45:59.048 --> 00:46:00.090
You shouldn't be smoking.

00:46:00.090 --> 00:46:02.290
You shouldn't take your
mask off for any reason.

00:46:08.470 --> 00:46:11.010
That's a high gamma
radiation warning sign.

00:46:11.010 --> 00:46:13.140
It was in fact, not that
high of a dose rate,

00:46:13.140 --> 00:46:14.880
somewhere in the range
of 30 mR an hour.

00:46:18.900 --> 00:46:24.930
We also explored a little bit
outside of the more formal part

00:46:24.930 --> 00:46:28.530
of the reactor
premises, namely we

00:46:28.530 --> 00:46:31.410
went to this place called
Buriakivka 2, which

00:46:31.410 --> 00:46:37.020
is a burial facility for
waste from the reactor,

00:46:37.020 --> 00:46:40.590
not waste as in nuclear waste
but waste is in chunks of metal

00:46:40.590 --> 00:46:42.900
and other things that are
contaminated and therefore

00:46:42.900 --> 00:46:45.900
removed when the New Safe
Confinement Arch was being

00:46:45.900 --> 00:46:49.950
built, or when, let's say, they
were building the separation

00:46:49.950 --> 00:46:52.232
wall between reactors 3 and 4.

00:46:52.232 --> 00:46:53.940
And there were some
incredibly hot spots.

00:46:53.940 --> 00:46:58.950
So I might, I think I have
some more photos later.

00:46:58.950 --> 00:47:02.340
But just under that
little triangle,

00:47:02.340 --> 00:47:08.850
the dose rate was 150 mR an
hour, so 0.15 rem an hour.

00:47:08.850 --> 00:47:10.420
It's extremely high.

00:47:10.420 --> 00:47:16.830
And that was just in a field
basically, not controlled, not

00:47:16.830 --> 00:47:19.180
patrolled, no warning signs.

00:47:21.840 --> 00:47:25.570
Getting dressed up, lots of fun.

00:47:25.570 --> 00:47:29.547
That was the truck we were
sent to decontaminate.

00:47:29.547 --> 00:47:31.380
Honestly it wasn't
particularly contaminated

00:47:31.380 --> 00:47:32.172
in the first place.

00:47:32.172 --> 00:47:35.870
They weren't going to give us
real fun things to play with.

00:47:35.870 --> 00:47:36.790
That's all of us.

00:47:36.790 --> 00:47:39.100
And then as you notice,
the real workers

00:47:39.100 --> 00:47:42.580
here are not wearing even
a fraction of what we are.

00:47:47.220 --> 00:47:56.450
More decontamination,
yeah, see, barely anything.

00:47:56.450 --> 00:47:58.950
These are chunks of metal that
have come out of the reactor.

00:47:58.950 --> 00:48:03.270
We're not exactly sure what
part, what parts they are.

00:48:03.270 --> 00:48:06.300
No one was really able to
answer our questions about them.

00:48:06.300 --> 00:48:08.430
But they were also
rather contaminated,

00:48:08.430 --> 00:48:10.740
somewhere in the
range of 50 to 75 mR

00:48:10.740 --> 00:48:15.160
an hour on contact
in some spots.

00:48:15.160 --> 00:48:18.952
More photos of Chernobyl, or
of Chernobyl from Pripyat.

00:48:18.952 --> 00:48:21.160
MICHAEL SHORT: Dr. Jake, I
want to take a quick break

00:48:21.160 --> 00:48:24.610
and ask folks if they
have any questions on what

00:48:24.610 --> 00:48:26.584
the experience was
like [INAUDIBLE]..

00:48:31.823 --> 00:48:32.490
JAKE HECLA: Yes?

00:48:32.490 --> 00:48:34.282
AUDIENCE: Did you suffer
any adverse health

00:48:34.282 --> 00:48:35.620
effects or anything?

00:48:35.620 --> 00:48:39.880
JAKE HECLA: Only the cold I
picked up on the way back.

00:48:39.880 --> 00:48:43.450
The total dose that I received
on this entire expedition,

00:48:43.450 --> 00:48:47.840
minus the flights there and
back, was 0.6 millisieverts.

00:48:47.840 --> 00:48:52.090
So effectively, nothing.

00:48:52.090 --> 00:48:53.710
MICHAEL SHORT: [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:53.710 --> 00:48:57.190
JAKE HECLA: Well, all of
the high radiation areas

00:48:57.190 --> 00:49:01.160
that we were in, we were
encouraged to walk quickly,

00:49:01.160 --> 00:49:03.880
is basically what
it comes down to.

00:49:03.880 --> 00:49:05.980
The time portion of time,
distance, and shielding

00:49:05.980 --> 00:49:09.300
was emphasized.

00:49:09.300 --> 00:49:11.010
Further questions?

00:49:11.010 --> 00:49:12.112
Yeah.

00:49:12.112 --> 00:49:15.290
AUDIENCE: Are there [INAUDIBLE]
radiation area versus

00:49:15.290 --> 00:49:16.232
[INAUDIBLE].

00:49:16.232 --> 00:49:17.940
Do they use the same
levels [INAUDIBLE]??

00:49:17.940 --> 00:49:21.570
JAKE HECLA: No, radiological
control in Ukraine

00:49:21.570 --> 00:49:25.950
is a totally different
game than it is in the US.

00:49:25.950 --> 00:49:29.190
There are the same
types of controls

00:49:29.190 --> 00:49:34.650
that exist in the US just
don't exist at that site.

00:49:34.650 --> 00:49:38.850
For areas that are immediately
dangerous to your health,

00:49:38.850 --> 00:49:41.250
you know, 10 rad
an hour, something

00:49:41.250 --> 00:49:44.130
like that, from what I
understand that there

00:49:44.130 --> 00:49:47.850
are locked doors that prevent
one from accessing those

00:49:47.850 --> 00:49:48.930
accidentally.

00:49:48.930 --> 00:49:51.250
And there are warning signs
in a variety of locations.

00:49:51.250 --> 00:49:55.560
But I don't think that there
is a the same standardization

00:49:55.560 --> 00:50:01.726
of 5 mR an hours is a radiation
area, et cetera, et cetera.

00:50:01.726 --> 00:50:02.226
Yeah.

00:50:05.530 --> 00:50:06.573
Further?

00:50:06.573 --> 00:50:08.240
MICHAEL SHORT: And
are folks still going

00:50:08.240 --> 00:50:10.200
to be running these tours
pretty continuously?

00:50:10.200 --> 00:50:10.940
JAKE HECLA: No.

00:50:10.940 --> 00:50:14.240
You won't be able to see the
sarcophagus itself because it

00:50:14.240 --> 00:50:17.870
will be contained within the
New Safe Confinement Arch

00:50:17.870 --> 00:50:19.890
pretty much now.

00:50:19.890 --> 00:50:22.550
It's 75, right, let's see.

00:50:22.550 --> 00:50:24.470
Last I checked, the New
Safe Confinement Arch

00:50:24.470 --> 00:50:29.660
was 75 percent of the way
over the reactor itself.

00:50:29.660 --> 00:50:32.030
Regular tourist
visits to Pripyat

00:50:32.030 --> 00:50:34.850
will continue to happen.

00:50:34.850 --> 00:50:37.640
This program that I went on
is something very special.

00:50:40.370 --> 00:50:45.800
Carl, Ed, and Erik have done
this type of thing once before.

00:50:45.800 --> 00:50:47.910
That was the trip I
went on last year.

00:50:47.910 --> 00:50:53.417
And they intend on doing it
once a year as long as they can.

00:50:53.417 --> 00:50:55.250
But that's pretty much
your only opportunity

00:50:55.250 --> 00:50:57.440
to get that kind of
access to the reactor.

00:50:57.440 --> 00:50:58.550
It takes a lot of work.

00:51:02.840 --> 00:51:05.280
MICHAEL SHORT: Anyone else
have questions for Jake?

00:51:05.280 --> 00:51:08.520
It's rare to meet someone that's
actually gone to Chernobyl to

00:51:08.520 --> 00:51:09.040
[INAUDIBLE].

00:51:09.040 --> 00:51:10.090
Yeah?

00:51:10.090 --> 00:51:11.970
AUDIENCE: Do you
think it's haunted?

00:51:11.970 --> 00:51:14.500
JAKE HECLA: No.

00:51:14.500 --> 00:51:17.080
There's a rather haunting
location, though,

00:51:17.080 --> 00:51:19.480
the Khodemchuk Memorial.

00:51:19.480 --> 00:51:22.750
So when the accident happened
there was one guy who was--

00:51:22.750 --> 00:51:26.080
depending on how you look at
it, either lucky or unlucky--

00:51:26.080 --> 00:51:28.390
in that he wasn't killed
by radiation poisoning.

00:51:28.390 --> 00:51:32.770
He was killed by being
flattened in the explosion.

00:51:32.770 --> 00:51:35.650
And his remains are
within the reactor

00:51:35.650 --> 00:51:39.162
and within the sarcophagus,
never really recovered him.

00:51:39.162 --> 00:51:40.870
Better than dying of
radiation poisoning.

00:51:40.870 --> 00:51:44.800
But nonetheless, not
a fantastic way to go.

00:51:44.800 --> 00:51:48.220
The memorial that is
within the sarcophagus

00:51:48.220 --> 00:51:53.770
is pretty interesting to
visit, and rather somber.

00:51:53.770 --> 00:51:56.920
Makes you reflect a little
bit on the enormous human toll

00:51:56.920 --> 00:51:59.220
that the accident had.